{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611145"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:09:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:09:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16203"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16203"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.94,0,0.03,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8894"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64313"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8894"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49745"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2290"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"10205"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21165"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21171"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64313"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPhysical growth during early life follows predictable patterns and is considered a key indicator of child health and development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the significance of growth during early life?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Growth failure during critical periods has permanent effects","Growth deficits can always be fully reversed later in childhood","Growth rate is constant throughout childhood","Growth patterns do not affect cognitive development","Growth velocity is independent of nutritional status"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth failure during critical periods has permanent effects\u003C/strong\u003E on development. These effects can include reduced adult height, impaired cognitive function, and altered metabolic programming. The first 1000 days of life are particularly crucial for establishing lifelong health trajectories.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth deficits can always be fully reversed later in childhood\u003C/strong\u003E - Some growth deficits, particularly those occurring during critical developmental windows, cannot be fully compensated for later\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth rate is constant throughout childhood\u003C/strong\u003E - Growth velocity varies significantly with age, with periods of rapid growth during infancy and puberty\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth patterns do not affect cognitive development\u003C/strong\u003E - Growth and cognitive development are closely linked, particularly during early life\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth velocity is independent of nutritional status\u003C/strong\u003E - Nutrition is a key determinant of growth velocity and overall growth potential\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegular growth monitoring helps identify problems early when interventions are most likely to be effective. Growth charts provide a standardised tool for tracking physical development and identifying concerning patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Growth during early life is critical for long-term health outcomes and development.","The first 1000 days of life (conception to age 2) represent a crucial window for physical growth and development.","Growth failure during critical periods can lead to permanent effects on height, cognitive development, and metabolic health."],"references":["Venkateshwar V, Raghu Raman TS. FAILURE TO THRIVE. Med J Armed Forces India. 2000 Jul;56(3):219-224. doi: 10.1016/S0377-1237(17)30171-5. Epub 2017 Jun 10. PMID: 28790712; PMCID: PMC5532051.","Ross E, Munoz FM, Edem B, Nan C, Jehan F, Quinn J, Mallett Moore T, Sesay S, Spiegel H, Fortuna L, Kochhar S, Buttery J; Brighton Collaboration Failure to Thrive Working Group. Failure to thrive: Case definition \u0026 guidelines for data collection, analysis, and presentation of maternal immunisation safety data. Vaccine. 2017 Dec 4;35(48 Pt A):6483-6491. doi: 10.1016/j.vaccine.2017.01.051. PMID: 29150053; PMCID: PMC5714432.","Hoddinott J, Behrman JR, Maluccio JA, Melgar P, Quisumbing AR, Ramirez-Zea M, Stein AD, Yount KM, Martorell R. Adult consequences of growth failure in early childhood. Am J Clin Nutr. 2013 Nov;98(5):1170-8. doi: 10.3945/ajcn.113.064584. Epub 2013 Sep 4. PMID: 24004889; PMCID: PMC3798075.","Cooke R, Goulet O, Huysentruyt K, Joosten K, Khadilkar AV, Mao M, Meyer R, Prentice AM, Singhal A. Catch-Up Growth in Infants and Young Children With Faltering Growth: Expert Opinion to Guide General Clinicians. J Pediatr Gastroenterol Nutr. 2023 Jul 1;77(1):7-15. doi: 10.1097/MPG.0000000000003784. Epub 2023 Mar 28. PMID: 36976274; PMCID: PMC10259217."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49745"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16203"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49745"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T12:11:15+10:30","updatedAt":"